o add. Should I include `testImplementation jna`? Is that the right choice for a test dependency? It looks like it targets a public API and uses native methods to create a pseudo-terminal and duplicate file descriptors rather than working with a library API. I need to think about the implications of it in a test environment setup — JNA might not work well with Native Image and could fail on metadata. Adding this dependency might not be a good idea.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JaCoCo agent usage**\\n\\nI'm noting that in the native parent, there's no JaCoCo agent being used. We're still able to spawn a child under the script without it, and the tests are passing with dynamic coverage from the javaTest child, which is great! I'm also wondering if the parent could run `AnsiOutput.setConsoleAvailable(Boolean.TRUE)` to exercise the API in native directly without a pty. That might be an interesting approach to explore!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering code style**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether checkstyle will have an issue with `main` being public in a test. It seems like it won’t really be a problem. I also realize I need to use type annotations for all variables effectively. Maybe I should start writing a test file to ensure I’m following the guidelines properly. It’s always good to stay consistent and clear—getting those details right really matters!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_yCRNFU9GWtOw0qRb4fAAjMmk|fc_034146b97de7a5d6016a252915e21881959ac1806036fd52d8", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.2/src/test/java/org_springframework_boot/spring_boot/AnsiOutputTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_springframework_boot.spring_boot;\n\nimport static org.ass